@graph.definition: Sandplains with weakly to moderately incised southerly valley and intervening hills and low ranges of granite and metamorphic rocks (extending as headlands and inlets). Bounded by latitudes 33.228449°S and 35.193981°S, and longitudes 117.406742°E and 123.719394°E.
Longitudinal dunes. Bounded by latitudes 26.565983°S and 27.346617°S, and longitudes 133.992033°E and 135.275623°E.

Dissected sandstone plateau. Bounded by latitudes 11.898184°S and 14.617665°S, and longitudes 132.164189°E and 135.636903°E.

Basaltic tableland. Bounded by latitudes 17.133515°S and 17.744619°S, and longitudes 145.307072°E and 145.897773°E.
Parallel ranges and dissected plateaus with intervening hardpan wash plains and stony plains. Bounded by latitudes 21.366927°S and 25.861701°S, and longitudes 114.943213°E and 120.791266°E.

Dissected high upland, glaciated locally with some periglacial features. Uplifted blocks surrounded by highly dissected high relief hill country. Bounded by latitudes 34.726109°S and 36.855898°S, and longitudes 147.086632°E and 149.207529°E.

Uplands and interior lowlands with a northwest–southeast trend parallel to and including coastal lowlands, dominated by the Fitzroy River catchment. Bounded by latitudes 14.222438°S and 23.423680°S, and longitudes 127.703369°E and 139.516732°E.

Undulating clay plains with minor stony limestone plains. Bounded by latitudes 21.944785°S and 23.067808°S, and longitudes 138.884884°E and 140.03994°E.
Plains, mainly alluvial, locally stony, with tidal flats. Bounded by latitudes 22.104335°S and 24.406156°S, and longitudes 151.600625°E and 149.366618°E.

Sandstone and basalt plateaus and lower rolling country on sedimentary and volcanic rocks. Bounded by latitudes 20.87373°S and 22.046464°S, and longitudes 148.654842°E and 147.957008°E.
Limestone plain with some salt lakes and sandplains. Bounded by latitudes 28.892723°S and 30.446088°S, and longitudes 124.581587°E and 130.545901°E.

Uplands and coastal areas of the western part of Cape York Peninsula, including the Great Escarpment. Bounded by latitudes 11.3029456°S and 20.864026°S, and longitudes 138.439832°E and 144.106039°E.

Narrow range of hills and dissected plateaus on basalt and sedimentary rocks. Bounded by latitudes 20.809919°S and 22.584392°S, and longitudes 116.050834°E and 120.103237°E.

Dissected plateau margin on granite and metamorphic rocks. Bounded by latitudes 28.328417°S and 30.346845°S, and longitudes 152.104399°E and 153.269257°E.
Coastal lowlands on weak sedimentary rocks, with littoral and alluvial plains. Bounded by latitudes 28.807524°S and 29.989761°S, and longitudes 152.819404°1E and 53.607544°E.

Plains of gravel and sandy alluvium. Bounded by latitudes 32.918201°S and 34.456489°S, and longitudes 146.850571°E and 148.371177°E.

The eastern uplands of Australia. Landform patterns reflect structural contrasts. Meridional folding and faulting are reflected in a general north–south grain of relief. It includes both the Great Divide and the Great Escarpment. Bounded by latitudes 9.141290°S and 43.860401°S, and longitudes 141.020610°E and 153.638336°E.
